solutions.content:
The way I build up my solution is as follows:

(`N` is the number of batteries, `C` is the number of computers, `battery` is sorted in non-increasing order and I have followed 1-based indexing).

First notice that if there were only `C` batteries, our answer would be nothing but the minimum of all values (it's nothing but `battery[C]`). 

Now assume that I have another battery whose `capacity <= battery[C]` (meaning there exists `battery[C+1]`)

Now, can we do anything with `battery[C+1]` to improve upon our current answer which is `battery[C]`?

Yes, we can use `battery[C+1]` as a filler and try to fill up `battery[C]` until it becomes equal to `battery[C-1]`. If there is still some part of this filler remaining, then we will increment both `battery[C]` and `battery[C-1]` simultaneouly, until it becomes equal to `battery[C-2]`. 

This step we can keep on performing until either `battery[C+1]` ends or all the batteries from `1 to C` becomes equal up. If all the batteries becomes equal and still `battery[C+1]` isn't exhausted, then we can use it equally among all `C` computers.

Now notice that the same argument can be extended for `battery[C+2], ... battery[N]`. So all these values can be used as filler and then we can try to level up the minimum value.

I hope I was able to provide an intuition for how this solution works.

Here's my accepted solution:
(Note: I have used `a` insted of `batteries` and 0-based indexing in the solution)

```
class Solution {
public:
    long long maxRunTime(int c, vector<int>& a) {
        int n = a.size();
        sort(a.rbegin(), a.rend());
        long long filler = 0;
        for(int i=c;i<n;i++) {
            filler += a[i];
        }
        long long ans = 0;
        for(int i=c-1;i-1>=0;i--) {
            long long diff = a[i-1]-a[i];
            long long req = diff * 1ll * (c - i);
            if(filler >= req) {
                filler -= req;
                ans = a[i-1];
            }
            else {
                ans = a[i] + (filler / (c - i));
                return ans;
            }
        }
        ans = a[0] + (filler / c);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

