# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The goal of the code is to find the maximum average time that can be achieved by distributing batteries among 'n' devices. The approach taken in the code is as follows:

1. Calculate the total time of all batteries.
2. Sort the batteries in descending order.
3. Start distributing the batteries with the highest time to the devices until one of the following conditions is met:
 a. All devices have received a battery (loop until 'n' becomes 0).
 b.The current battery's time is less than or equal to the average time calculated by dividing the total time by the number of remaining devices ('n').

   Once the loop is done, the code returns the maximum average time.

# Complexity
  - Time complexity:  O (n log n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ --> 


- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

class Solution {
public:
    long long maxRunTime(int n, vector<int>& bat) {
        // Calculate the total time of all batteries
        long long total_time = 0;
        for (int x : bat) {
            total_time += x;
        }

        // Sort batteries in descending order
        sort(bat.rbegin(), bat.rend(),);

        // Distribute batteries to achieve maximum average time
        for (int i = 0; i < bat.size(); i++, n--) {
            if (bat[i] <= (total_time / n)) {
                break;
            }
            total_time -= bat[i];
        }

        // Return the maximum average time
        return total_time / n;
    }
};

```

