solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Look at this case below:
```
3
[1000, 1, 1, 1]
```
Although we have a 1000-minute battery, we can run the computers for only 1 minutes. 

The 1000 battery is over capacity. Put it aside and the case is transformed to:
```
2
[1, 1, 1]
```
The sum of [1, 1, 1] divided by 2 equals 1 (1.5 exactly), so the final output is 1. It has nothing to do with 1000.

Leave out all over capacity batteries, and then, average capacity of  remained batteries will be the answer. 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. sort vector b in descending order
2. calculate the sum of vector b 
3. leave out all over-capacity batteries 
4. return the value of the last avg

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n + m)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Note: m = battery number

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long maxRunTime(int n, vector<int>& b) {
        sort(b.rbegin(), b.rend());

        long long sum = 0, avg = 0;
        for (int x: b) sum += x;

        int index = 0;
        while (n > 0 && b[index] > (avg = sum / n)) {
            sum -= b[index++];
            n--;
        }

        return avg;
    }
};
```

