# Intuition
The given problem aims to find the maximum run time for a device with n batteries, given their power levels. So we use binary search to efficiently find the maximum run time that can be achieved. We iteratively adjust the search range based on the available power and the required power for n batteries at the target run time. The binary search narrows down the search space to find the maximum achievable run time, optimizing the solution.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach

Steps:
- Calculate the sum of all power levels in the batteries vector.
- Initialize the binary search range with left = 1 (minimum run time) and right = sumPower / n (maximum run time if all batteries have an equal share of power).
- Perform binary search to find the maximum achievable run time.
- In each iteration, calculate the target run time as the middle value between left and right.
- Check if the batteries can support the target run time by calculating the total power available (extra) while considering the minimum power needed for n batteries at the target run time.
- Adjust the search range based on the available power (extra):
1) If extra is sufficient, set left = target to search for higher possible run times.
2) If extra is insufficient, set right = target - 1 to search for lower possible run times.
- Continue the binary search until left becomes greater than or equal to right.
- Return the maximum achievable run time (left).
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(m log k) where, m is the length of the input array batteries and k be the maximum power of one battery.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(1)
